AGI - The Princess of Wales began preventive chemotherapy after her doctors discovered cancer after an important abdominal surgery in January. The Guardian explains what preventive chemotherapy is and how effective can it be? What is preventive chemotherapy? Treatment, formally known as adjuvant chemotherapy, is a cycle of antitumor drugs administered to absorb any tumor cells that could remain in the body after primary cancer treatment, which is usually surgical removal of a tumor.
&nbsp;
What are you doing? The therapy aims to reduce the risk that original cancer recurs and spreads. This can happen when cancer cells, which are too small to be detected with scans and hospital tests, remain after surgery. The risk of cancer relapse tends to be less if cancer is diagnosed in a very early stage, before it has had the opportunity to spread, but greater if the disease is found in a later stage or spread to nearby lymph nodes.
&nbsp;
How does therapy work? Most antitumoral chemotherapy drugs target cells that divide quickly. A typical cycle of preventive chemotherapy lasts from three to six months depending on the type and stage of cancer, which is determined by examining cancer removed during surgery. Occasionally, adjuvant chemotherapy cycles are administered for several years. How many therapy cycles do people follow? It depends on the nature of the original tumor detected after surgery. When cancer is discovered during surgery for other pathologies, cancer is often at an early stage when subsequent chemotherapy is more effective.
&nbsp;
"This probably means that a single chemotherapy cycle will be enough to ensure that, if there are cancer cells, they will be destroyed", says Professor Lawrence Young, director of Warwick Cancer Research Center at the University of Warwick. How effective is therapy? is particularly effective against breast cancer, intestines and lungs, but can also be recommended for other forms of the disease. For example, adjuvant chemotherapy is often used after surgery for ovary epithelial cancer, the most common form of ovarian cancer, due to the risk of relapse of the disease. Doctors decide whether adjuvant therapy can benefit from cancer, advanced stage of the disease and other tumor properties.
&nbsp;
Are there any side effects? No chemotherapy is completely harmless. Side effects depend on specific medications administered, but patients may experience tiredness, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, an increase in the risk of contracting infections and loss of appetite. Side effects occur because drugs affect not only cancer cells but all cells that divide quickly, including hair, bone marrow, skin and digestive system lining. Damage to healthy tissues however tends to be temporary and side effects usually disappear once the treatment is finished. Young people often tolerate better chemotherapy than older patients and experience less side effects thanks to their "more functional reserves" and the "ability of young tissues to heal faster", says Dr. Mangesh Thorat, Honorary Reader at Queen Mary University in London.
&nbsp;
For this reason, young people can be given higher doses of drugs, which are more likely to eliminate any remaining cancer cells in their bodies. How long does it take to recover? It depends on the patient and the particular medications administered, but it may be necessary several months before a person returns to full strength. As young people tend to be healthier and in shape than the elderly, their recovery times are generally shorter.

